Solution: The given probabilities are \(P(A \cup B) = 0.76\) and \(P(A \cup B') = 0.87\). The probability of the union of these two events covers the entire sample space, so \(P((A \cup B) \cup (A \cup B')) = 1\). The intersection of \(A \cup B\) and \(A \cup B'\) is \(A\), so \(P((A \cup B) \cap (A \cup B')) = P(A)\).

Using the inclusion-exclusion principle:  
\[P((A \cup B) \cup (A \cup B')) = P(A \cup B) + P(A \cup B') - P((A \cup B) \cap (A \cup B'))\]  
Substituting the known values:  
\[1 = 0.76 + 0.87 - P(A)\]  
\[1 = 1.63 - P(A)\]  
\[P(A) = 1.63 - 1 = 0.63\]

