Problem: Calculate the magnitude of the spin angular momentum of a proton. Give a numerical answer.  The unit of the answer should be  $10^{-35} \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~s}$.
Solution: The magnitude of the spin angular momentum for any spin-1/2 particle, such as a proton, is given by \( S = \sqrt{\frac{1}{2} \left( \frac{1}{2} + 1 \right)} \hbar = \sqrt{\frac{3}{4}} \hbar = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \hbar \), where \( \hbar \) is the reduced Planck's constant.

Using \( \hbar \approx 1.0545718 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J·s} \) and \( \sqrt{3} \approx 1.7320508 \), the calculation is:
\[
S = \frac{1.7320508}{2} \times 1.0545718 \times 10^{-34} = 0.8660254 \times 1.0545718 \times 10^{-34} \approx 9.13293 \times 10^{-35} \, \text{J·s}.
\]

Rounded to three significant figures, \( S \approx 9.13 \times 10^{-35} \, \text{J·s} \). In the required units of \( 10^{-35} \, \text{J·s} \), the numerical value is 9.13.

